Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks — without it you get race conditions.
- `args.Cancel()` prevents the navigation.
- `deferral.Complete()` signals Shell to proceed (or not, if cancelled).

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button in `EditProductPage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard above still applies
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

Since the `CancelCommand` uses `GoToAsync("..")`, it will trigger `OnNavigating` with `ShellNavigationSource.Pop`, so the same unsaved-changes guard applies to both the hardware/software back button and your custom "Cancel" button.
